@startuml
' Filename: Beam_System_State_Diagram.plantuml
' Diagram Type: State Diagram
' Authored 2026-07-18 from the live engine: src/simulation/behavior/beam-arbitrator.ts
' (stepBeamArbitrator) and src/simulation/oscillator-step.ts (stepOscillator, the motor).
'
' The Beam arbitrates between the two Male units mounted at either end of the
' rotating bar, then drives its single motor. Priority (internal_dominant_address)
' decides who MAY take the beam; a per-end LATCH (internal_holding_address, firmware
' I_barStopRequest / II_barStopRequest) decides who actually HOLDS it. The motor
' obeys the latch, not the priority - a rising drive cannot steal the beam
' mid-exchange. Transitions are re-evaluated every tick.

[*] --> Released

state "Released (oscillate)" as Released {
  ' holdingAddress = null   ->   beamMotorMode = "release"
  ' neither end asking, or the asking end lacks priority AND has no latch yet
  ' motor: free oscillation between the beam's left / right limits
}

state "Holding end I" as HoldingI {
  ' latchedI = true   ->   holdingAddress = "I", beamMotorMode = "hold"
  ' motor goal beamTargetAngle = reinforcementPositionI
  '   = normalize(closestFemale(maleIWorldAngle) - maleIOffset)
  ' re-evaluated every tick as the beam approaches the target
}

state "Holding end II" as HoldingII {
  ' latchedII = true   ->   holdingAddress = "II", beamMotorMode = "hold"
  ' motor goal beamTargetAngle = reinforcementPositionII
  '   = normalize(closestFemale(maleIIWorldAngle) - maleIIOffset)
}

' Acquire needs ALL of: this end is asking (stop_request), this end has priority
' (driveI >= driveII -> I; tie -> I), AND the other end holds no latch.
Released --> HoldingI : stopRequestI AND driveI >= driveII\nAND end II not latched
Released --> HoldingII : stopRequestII AND driveII > driveI\nAND end I not latched

' Release beats acquire: a latch drops the instant its own male stops asking.
' Hold ignores priority - the beam is held until its own male lets go.
HoldingI --> Released : stopRequestI = false\n(end I lets go)
HoldingII --> Released : stopRequestII = false\n(end II lets go)

' Handover cannot be direct: end II must wait one tick after end I releases
' (firmware evaluation order - end I's block updates the latch end II then reads).
HoldingI --> HoldingII : end I released last tick, then\nstopRequestII AND end II gains priority
HoldingII --> HoldingI : end II released last tick, then\nstopRequestI AND end I gains priority

legend right
  Source: src/simulation/behavior/beam-arbitrator.ts (stepBeamArbitrator).
  Canonical frame-variable keys:
  - sense_drive_level_I / sense_drive_level_II   (each Male's dominant drive)
  - sense_stop_request_I / sense_stop_request_II (the "stop" the bar senses)
  - internal_dominant_address  (priority: who MAY take the beam; tie -> "I")
  - internal_holding_address   (the latch: who actually HOLDS it)
  - internal_goal_position_I / _II  (closest-Female world angle per end)
  Motor mode = release (oscillate) | hold (move to reinforcement position).
  RAW drives by design - the averaging existed only for hardware noise.
endlegend

@enduml
